UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1955
1 A JOINT RESOLUTION directing the Auditor of Public Accounts to study the
2 applicable statutes, administrative regulations, and agency policies and processes that
3 directly impact the opening and operation of licensed and certified child care services in
4 the Commonwealth.
5 WHEREAS, recent research demonstrates that access to licensed and certified child
6 care services is necessary to support workforce participation in the Commonwealth; and
7 WHEREAS, recent research demonstrates that many Kentucky communities face
8 challenges in ensuring access to child care services for working families; and
9 WHEREAS, the Kentucky General Assembly has identified the need to create a
10 consensus-driven process to ease regulatory burdens on current and future child care
11 providers while ensuring the safety of children and quality child care and early childhood
12 education services in the Commonwealth;
13 NOW, THEREFORE,
14 Be it resolved by the General Assembly of the Commonwealth of Kentucky:
15 Section 1. (1) The Auditor of Public Accounts shall contract with a
16 qualified and independent third party to conduct a comprehensive study of applicable
17 statutes, administrative regulations, and agency policies and processes that directly
18 impact the opening and operation of licensed and certified child care services in the
19 Commonwealth. The Auditor of Public Accounts shall submit a final report and
20 recommendations to reform, streamline, and modernize or maintain existing statutes,
21 administrative regulations, and agency policies and processes governing the licensing and
22 certification of child care programs to the Legislative Research Commission by
23 December 1, 2027, for referral to the Interim Joint Committee on Families and Children.
24 (2) Key elements of the study shall include but not be limited to:
25 (a) An evaluation of existing Kentucky statutes, administrative regulations, and
26 agency policies and processes governing the licensing and certification of child care
27 programs to identify statutory, regulatory, and administrative barriers to starting and
Page 1 of 4
