UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1955
1 operating licensed and certified child care services;
2 (b) A comparison of Kentucky’s statutes, administrative regulations, and agency
3 policies and processes governing the licensing and certification of child care programs to
4 those in peer states and to the recommendations and guidelines of the most recent edition
5 of Caring for our Children: National Health and Safety Performance Standards;
6 Guidelines for Early Care and Education Programs;
7 (c) A detailed analysis of how federal laws impact state statutes, administrative
8 regulations, and agency policies and processes governing the licensing and certification
9 of child care programs;
10 (d) An identification of instances where existing statutes, administrative
11 regulations, and agency policies and processes governing the licensing and certification
12 of child care programs are duplicative, confusing, excessive, or ineffective;
13 (e) Surveys and focus groups of key stakeholders, including but not limited to the
14 Kentucky Child Care Advisory Council, licensed and certified child care providers, early
15 childhood educators employed in licensed and certified child care programs, executive
16 branch officials involved in regulating licensed and certified child care providers,
17 representatives from local child care resource and referral agencies, public policy experts
18 with expertise in child care issues, legal professionals with expertise in child care issues,
19 experts in issues related to child welfare and child abuse prevention, pediatric care
20 professionals, small business coaching services, parents of young children, advocates for
21 individuals with special needs, early childhood education professionals at colleges and
22 universities based in Kentucky, and Kentucky employers;
23 (f) Recommendations for licensed and certified child care sectors to make greater
24 use of the General Regulatory Sandbox Program established in KRS 15.268; and
25 (g) Recommendations for administrative regulations to allow for outdoor, nature-
26 based early learning and child care programs.
27 (3) The study shall include surveys and focus groups on existing statutes,
Page 2 of 4
BR195500.100 - 1955 - XXXX 2/18/2026 2:35 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1955
1 administrative regulations, and agency policies and processes governing the licensing and
2 certification of child care programs from nonlicensed and noncertified child care
3 providers. In addition, the study shall gather quantitative and qualitative data from a wide
4 range of licensed and certified child care providers, including providers operating in
5 different regions of the state, having different ratings under the Kentucky All STARS
6 program, providing faith-based and nonfaith-based programing, serving various numbers
7 of children, and serving children from families of various income levels. In gathering
8 data, the study shall guarantee anonymity to participating stakeholders to the greatest
9 extent possible.
10 (4) The study shall exclude from the scope of review analysis of child-to-teacher
11 ratios and maximum group sizes.
12 (5) In addition to the key study elements listed in subsection (2) of this section,
13 the study shall include an analysis of local regulatory barriers to child care services and
14 shall recommend best practices for local governments to utilize when evaluating local
15 ordinances, regulations, and zoning and land-use rules pertaining to the availability of
16 child care services in local communities in alignment with the Certified Child Care
17 Community Designation Program established in KRS 199.891. These recommendations
18 and best practices shall focus on balancing health and safety with increasing the supply of
19 child care services and easing local regulatory barriers, and shall include but not be
20 limited to the following topics:
21 (a) Local land-use policies and zoning ordinances related to child care services,
22 including but not limited to:
23 1. Recommendations for definitions for terms such as "child care," "licensed
24 child-care center," "licensed family child-care center," "child-care microcenter," and
25 "certified family child-care home";
26 2. Recommendations on where child care services should be permitted by right,
27 with special standards, and with conditional use permits;
Page 3 of 4
BR195500.100 - 1955 - XXXX 2/18/2026 2:35 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1955
1 3. Recommendations for requirements for compliance with conditional use
2 permits and special standards;
3 4. Best practices for safely permitting child care services in or near industrial
4 areas;
5 5. Best practices for playgrounds associated with child care services; and
6 6. Recommendations for parking and drop-off and pick-up requirements, where
7 applicable;
8 (b) Policies pertaining to local permitting fees for starting and operating child
9 care services or any other type of local fee impacting child care services; and
10 (c) Policies related to other local ordinances and regulations that may pertain to
11 the availability of child care services in local communities.
12 (6) In recommending best practices for local governments, the study shall include
13 surveys and focus groups of various stakeholders, including local government officials
14 representing different types of communities and regions from around the state, planning
15 and design professionals, licensed and certified child care providers, representatives from
16 child care resource and referral agencies, public policy experts with expertise in child
17 care issues, legal professionals with expertise in child care issues, local law enforcement
18 professionals, local health departments, fire marshals, and employers.
19 (7) The qualified and independent third party under contract with the Auditor of
20 Public Accounts shall routinely consult and collaborate with the Kentucky Child Care
21 Advisory Council established in KRS 199.8983 during the course of its analysis and as it
22 develops recommendations for the final report. The qualified and independent third party
23 shall seek feedback from the council, shall provide quarterly updates to the council, and
24 shall submit a draft final report to the council for review by November 1, 2027.
